,Recommended,429720,21601861,"Posted: 3 March, 2016",all,skooch,"One of the only refreshingly unique horror games released in the last few yearsAnd that statement would hold true even for the precursor to this game, a free indie title released more than a year ago. IMSCARED has been a long time coming into its current incarnation into a full game,but it lives up to it's 5 dollar price tag just fine, and then some.It's hard to explain how good this game is without spoiling any of the experience, but here goes.The horror game genre is undoubtedly gimmicky and saturated like the film one, it's hard to find something that truly suprises a die-hard participant in the genre.IMSCARED is the one of a kind exception.Some may argue over the pixelated art style, the cliche ""meta"" gameplay, or even just the length of the title. But I disagree, it's these things and how well they're done that make this game truly shine.Where others have simply copied and combined aspects of previous works, Ivan (the developer of IMSCARED) has outdone himself to the point where this game simply excels at being, well, horrific. There is a moment in this game to scare everyone and give them the chills, not a single opportunity is wasted to let you know the situation you have gotten yourself into.IMSCARED doesn't get old, not in the sense that it has replay value, but it is true:once you complete this game in its entirety you will not look at any horror game the same way again.What this title does is excite you while unsettling the hell out of you for the entirety of the experience, from the start to the very end (oh, and I do mean very end, this game while technically short, feels like a lifetime to complete in the very best way possible).Suffice to say, buy this damn game already. I've never written any reviews for Steam before, but this game is the one I just had to. That should be all you need to know.Oh and just one last thing.Forgive me."
,Recommended,429720,30403675,Posted: 8 March,all,t. mike,"Not brilliant, but innovative as heck and worth it for all the experimentation it gets into. The game twists your expectations of gaming and kills itself -- literally quits out (often during spooky moments) -- in order to keep you from progressing. You have to wade through obscure YouTube videos and .txt files populating your desktop to try to unravel what's going on and unlock the next segment of the game.IMSCARED has three endings staggered by more gameplay and story. The story's nothing special, but it's interesting enough (and creepy enough) underneath the shattered 4th wall and quirky puzzles. The way this game progresses...it really feels like the game speaks to you and responds to your actions. Great stuff."
