,Not Recommended,429720,21678031,"Posted: 6 March, 2016",all,seanson,"IMSCARED has a few original ideas, but really fell flat in the end. There are different environments that you traipse through, each with a different atmosphere, but nothing felt intuitive or exciting. Sometimes there's a hidden key you haven't found, and sometimes you have to go check out files that the game is creating on your desktop. Sometimes you even have to close and restart the game yourself to continue. The fact that the game never communicates what you have to do to advance can sometimes create situations in which you're not sure if you should be looking around harder because you missed something, or if you should write a five page essay and submit it to the game. The fourth wall bits are interesting but poorly implemented for a cohesive horror experience.The story is weak and vague, the graphics have a nice style but make text illegible, and the jumpscares were mostly unnecessary. Some parts of the game rely on sound within a 3D soundscape, and sound seems to originate in one position but does not change relative to your movement. Certain actions like climbing a ladder or printing tickets have a gratingly loud volume for no reason.Many achievements were very arbitrary, and ended up being necessary to finish the game. Oh, and if you want to go back to get the achievements, have fun figuring out the ridiculous hallway hub. 2 doors go to 2 areas, one door with a pickup is needed to access a password screen to get to 2 other areas. It's as dumb as it sounds.IMGLAD that I didn't pay more than $4, which still seems too steep for the overall quality of this ""game,""  or waste more than 2 hours getting achievements to see the loud, lame ending. It's an experience, but one that I could have lived just fine without."
