76561198033604792,Not Recommended,429720,29392538,Posted: 21 January,all,Meeg,"IAMSCARED is not like other games. It’s “meta” and it’s spooky. I can see how the designer was aiming to create a unique experience, and I commend him for this, but in the end I think he was only partially successful in the execution of his goal and in creating a game I wanted to play. I ended up just watching my friend play through most of it and if it was only me I would have given up before I finished.My thoughts (very mild spoilers ahead):* The meta-puzzles (puzzles which require you to look outside the game itself) are clever and out of the ordinary.* The more traditional puzzles are all pretty simple. The answer is usually obvious although sometimes you might have a hard time because of the game controls or because you can’t find something.* For the most part the game succeeds in creating an eerie atmosphere. The sound, the way the environment looks, the creepy messages and enigmatic characters….* As others have pointed out, part of the scare factor is a result of your annoyingly small field of vision. You can only see like five feet in front of you so it’s easy to run into something surprising.* Related to the limited field of vision, the game has a lot of jump scares. These are fun at first but get old fast, especially if you are caught by the monster and have to replay the same part again and again. This is frustrating; but more than that it can destroy the scare factor.* The controls! You need to use the WASD keys to move around (this alone is almost a deal breaker for me) and the game is not very responsive, so your movements are jerky. It’s also easy to get stuck in a corner or at the edge of a wall (this is  just a result of poor game design/programming). It’s particularly frustrating in parts where you’re being chased and need to run.*The graphics and the environment: I have mixed feelings. I see what the designer was going for with very basic, very retro graphics. The game’s look reminded me of EGA computer games and also the LSD: Dream Emulator on Playstation. So this gives the game a dream/nightmare vibe and it fits well with the “deconstructing the game” aspect of IAMSCARED. On the other hand, this really goes beyond artfully pixelated and sometimes just feels insufficiently detailed (get close enough to something and you’ll see it’s just colored blocks).* More than the graphics, I disliked the low level of interactivity. 90% of the objects you see (bookcases, cabinets, tables, shopping carts) are just decoration you can do nothing with. You’ll spend a lot of the game going up to things and trying to interact with them only to find out “nope.”*Related to the simple puzzles and the static non-interactive environment, there are a lot of times when it seemed like I reached a dead-end and needed to do something (like find a key or a secret passage or something) but the answer was that I needed to trigger something like a “cut scene” and then when I came back the way would be clear.*The story: again mixed feelings. In the game you’ll encounter one or two important characters. You’re given vague hints as to what their story is, but it’s left pretty fuzzy. On one hand, this is good because you need to fill in the blanks yourself and it’s open to interpretation. On the other hand, maybe there’s just not enough there.*That leads into my final gripe which is that there’s no pay off. Towards the very end, the game throws up such a barrier it’s almost like the designer doesn’t want you to finish the game. And the ending(s?) are kind of anti-climactic; it made me question whether it was even worth it.TL;DR: All-in-all, if I put aside the annoying controls, I’d say I got something out of IAMSCARED and enjoyed the unique meta-puzzles but so many things frustrated or bored me that I would never have finished the game on my own."
